overview: The user initiated a request to fix a problematic pull request, citing
  numerous issues and failing Vercel deploys. The process began with a
  comprehensive review of the PR comments, identifying critical security flaws
  (forgeable auth cookie, unbounded pagination), various bugs (PDF generation,
  form field handling, UI elements), and lint errors. The initial lint errors
  were found to be locally resolved, but the security and functional issues
  required significant code changes. A key challenge was ensuring the
  authentication system worked securely within Vercel's Edge Runtime, leading to
  a refactor using the Web Crypto API. Subsequent Vercel deployment failures led
  to the discovery and resolution of a critical Next.js security vulnerability
  (CVE-2025-66478), which necessitated updating Next.js to v16.1.1. This update,
  in turn, introduced breaking changes in ESLint configuration and Prisma client
  initialization, requiring further fixes. Finally, outdated e2e tests were
  updated to reflect the current application. The persistent debugging and
  iterative fixes ultimately resulted in a fully functional, secure application
  with all GitHub Actions and Vercel deployments passing.
